1️⃣ VirtualBox Network Setup

Each router needs 2 adapters:

Adapter 1: NAT (internet, optional)

Adapter 2: Internal Network for lab traffic

If routers are on different internal networks (sw01 vs sw02):

Either put both routers on the same Internal Network (simplest)

Or use a third router between sw01 and sw02 to route traffic

Example (same network):

Router A (Server) ether2: 192.168.10.1/24
Router B (Client) ether2: 192.168.10.2/24

Ping to confirm:

Router B → ping 192.168.10.1
Router A → ping 192.168.10.2
2️⃣ Configure PPTP Server (Router A)
/interface pptp-server server set enabled=yes
/ip pool add name=pptp_pool ranges=10.10.10.2-10.10.10.10
/ppp profile add name=pptp_profile local-address=10.10.10.1 remote-address=pptp_pool
/ppp secret add name=client password=123 service=pptp profile=pptp_profile
3️⃣ Configure PPTP Client (Router B)
/interface pptp-client add connect-to=192.168.10.1 user=client password=123 name=pptp-out1 disabled=no

Check tunnel:

/interface print
ping 10.10.10.1

Server IP: 10.10.10.1

Client IP: 10.10.10.2

4️⃣ Add Routes to Internal LANs

Example LANs:

Router	LAN Network
Server	192.168.1.0/24
Client	192.168.2.0/24
On Server (Router A)
/ip route add dst-address=192.168.2.0/24 gateway=10.10.10.2
On Client (Router B)
/ip route add dst-address=192.168.1.0/24 gateway=10.10.10.1

Test connectivity:

Router B → ping 192.168.1.1
Router A → ping 192.168.2.1

